lead_paragraph: THE leaders of the troubled industrial nations who left the Versailles summit meeting in June heralding their common purpose and proclaiming their good will are hissing at each other today like so many alley cats.
abstract: THE leaders of the troubled industrial nations who left the Versailles summit meeting in June heralding their common purpose and proclaiming their good will are hissing at each other today like so many alley cats.   ''The United States seems totally indifferent to our problems,'' charges French Foreign Minister Claude Cheysson, defending his Government's decision to defy President Reagan and proceed with construction of the Soviet gas pipeline. West German Chancellor Helmut Schmidt endorsed the French action and sounded a similar note. Washington's handling of the pipeline, he said, has ''cast a shadow over relations'' between Europe and the United States, ''damaging confidence as regards future agreements.''   But it's not just the pipeline that has made a mockery of Versailles. Charges of unfair trade practices and threats of retaliation in a half-dozen industries are flying back and forth over the Atlantic -and the Pacific, too - in a worrisome crescendo.  Businessmen, dismayed by the long seige of sluggish economic growth that has left some 30 million people in the West unemployed, are doing what comes naturally: pressuring politicians to restrain imports, subsidize exports, or both. Steelmakers in Bonn and Pittsburgh want help; so do auto makers in London and Detroit, textile, apparel and shoe manufacturers throughout the West and farmers virtually everywhere.

lead_paragraph: The Reagan Administration, moving to revive the chances for approval of its $350 million aid program for the Caribbean region, sent the Secretaries of State and the Treasury and other officials to Capitol Hill today to press for the proposal.
abstract: The Reagan Administration, moving to revive the chances for approval of its $350 million aid program for the Caribbean region, sent the Secretaries of State and the Treasury and other officials to Capitol Hill today to press for the proposal.   Secretary of State George P. Shultz, in his first appearance before Congress since his confirmation hearing, told the Senate Finance Committee approval was needed to reaffirm the United States commitment to Latin America after the war in the Falklands.   ''Our security and credibility are at stake,'' Mr. Shultz said.  ''The tragic war in the South Atlantic has led some hemispheric friends - mistakenly I believe - to challenge our commitment to them as a partner. We must show them that this is not so.'' Mr. Shultz simply read his statement, then left for a White House meeting.

abstract: AGROUP of county commuters dissatisfied with Conrail service filed individual suits against the rail line last week for ''breach of contract of carriage.'' By last Wednesday 15 commuters had officially filed suits in Small Claims Courts countywide, with another 11 expected to file within the next few weeks, according to Paul Feiner, the Scarsdale activist who spearheaded the legal actions.   All but one of the plaintiffs is seeking $,1500 in punitive damages - the maximum allowed in small claims actions. One commuter is asking that the cost of the monthly commuter ticket be refunded.   A hearing date has been set for Sept. 22 in White Plains for the five suits filed there last Tuesday. Other claims were filed in Greenburgh, Scarsdale, Eastchester, Harrison, New Rochelle and Yonkers. No hearing dates have been set for the other cases.

An overlooked and a highly significant cause of recession-proof high interest rates and the overall sluggish economy is the role of commercial banks and their deregulation by the Federal Government.

Supply-side strategists and liberal spenders al...
lead_paragraph: An overlooked and a highly significant cause of recession-proof high interest rates and the overall sluggish economy is the role of commercial banks and their deregulation by the Federal Government.
abstract:
An overlooked and a highly significant cause of recession-proof high interest rates and the overall sluggish economy is the role of commercial banks and their deregulation by the Federal Government.

Supply-side strategists and liberal spenders alike subscribe to the belief that increased capital formation is the essence of a sound economy, bolstering America's productivity and thereby reducing inflation and improving the nation's international competitiveness.  But the Reagan Administration's monetary and fiscal policies have only succeeded in producing the opposite effects. Ruinous interest rates are the soft underbelly of supply-side Reaganomics. Merely keeping a business afloat has become the manager's No. 1 task. Today, nearly 50 cents of every dollar of cash flow to American corporations goes to pay off debt obligations. Under this tragic scenario, many enterprises have failed; for those still surviving, long-term investment plans - building efficient plants, installing modern equipment, engaging in research and development - have become economically unfeasible.

lead_paragraph: In a new set of rulings expected to aggravate trade tensions with Europe, the Commerce Department said today that five Common Market countries and Rumania illegally dumped steel in the United States by selling it at prices as much as 41 percent below ''fair value.''
abstract: In a new set of rulings expected to aggravate trade tensions with Europe, the Commerce Department said today that five Common Market countries and Rumania illegally dumped steel in the United States by selling it at prices as much as 41 percent below ''fair value.''   The ruling, a preliminary finding, means that stiff duties could be levied on steel imports from Britain, France, Belgium, West Germany and Italy as well as Rumania. The duties would bring the price of the imported steel products up to what the Commerce Department considered a fair market level.   The latest action would have to be confirmed in a final Commerce Department ruling, due by Oct. 25, before duties could actually be imposed.

lead_paragraph: Robert W. Woodruff, a college dropout who became the driving force behind the growth of the Coca-Cola Company and built it into an international financial empire, died today in Emory University Hospital. He was 95 years old and had been hospitalized for 10 days.
abstract: Robert W. Woodruff, a college dropout who became the driving force behind the growth of the Coca-Cola Company and built it into an international financial empire, died today in Emory University Hospital. He was 95 years old and had been hospitalized for 10 days.    Mr. Woodruff took control of the company in 1923. He retired in 1955, but remained as a director and chairman of the finance committee of the board of directors until 1981, when he became chairman emeritus. He left the board in 1984, ending a 61-year association with the company.    Throughout his life, Mr. Woodruff gave millions of dollars, almost always anonymously, to education and cultural institutions, including $200 million to Emory University.

lead_paragraph: The outlook for interest rates continues to be clouded, but the trend since the end of January has definitely been up. Treasury yields have been creeping up on both long- and short-term instruments despite the Federal Reserve's insistence that monetary policy has not been tightened. Indeed, the narrowest measure of the money supply, M-1, has been rising, and the latest week's increase of $3.6 billion pushed M-1 almost $9 billion above the Fed's target. And while the Federal Home Loan Bank Board reported that mortgage rates dropped in February for the seventh month, the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corporation said they began rising in mid-February. Still, some analysts say any increases in rates will not last in the face of a booming economy with controlled inflation.
abstract: The outlook for interest rates continues to be clouded, but the trend since the end of January has definitely been up. Treasury yields have been creeping up on both long- and short-term instruments despite the Federal Reserve's insistence that monetary policy has not been tightened. Indeed, the narrowest measure of the money supply, M-1, has been rising, and the latest week's increase of $3.6 billion pushed M-1 almost $9 billion above the Fed's target. And while the Federal Home Loan Bank Board reported that mortgage rates dropped in February for the seventh month, the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corporation said they began rising in mid-February. Still, some analysts say any increases in rates will not last in the face of a booming economy with controlled inflation.      The Fed chairman did little to clear up the confusion. Paul A. Volcker seemed to favor continued intervention in the currency markets by central banks, which could send interest rates higher. But he also said a significant cut in the Federal deficit could lead to lower rates.

lead_paragraph: Australia has often been called a ''lucky country'' because of all its natural resources. With world commodity prices depressed, however, fear is growing among Australians that the era of easy prosperity has passed, that their country's luck may be running out.
abstract: Australia has often been called a ''lucky country'' because of all its natural resources. With world commodity prices depressed, however, fear is growing among Australians that the era of easy prosperity has passed, that their country's luck may be running out.    These worries have heightened in recent weeks with Australia's international accounts deficit mounting and its currency plummeting not only against the vigorous United States dollar but against other major currencies as well.   Foreign-exchange dealers have dubbed the Australian dollar the ''antipodean peso.'' Some commentators have warned that Australia is on its way to becoming the ''Argentina of the Pacific.''

lead_paragraph: The Soviet Union wants to become a major force in the development and use of communications satellites for television broadcasting, high-speed data transmission and other telecommunication services, American officials and other analysts said today.
abstract: The Soviet Union wants to become a major force in the development and use of communications satellites for television broadcasting, high-speed data transmission and other telecommunication services, American officials and other analysts said today.    They made their comments in response to the tentative agreement reached between Moscow and the 109- nation International Telecommunications Satellite Organization on an exchange of information. The agreement, which was disclosed Tuesday, is expected to lead to Soviet membership in the communications network, which was founded by the United States 21 years ago.    But the American officials said the relationship could cause ''problems'' if Moscow tries to use it to acquire advanced technology that is barred by American export regulations.

lead_paragraph: Almost four years ago, President Reagan visited Canada on his first official trip abroad. He came to complain to Pierre Elliott Trudeau, then Prime Minister.
abstract: Almost four years ago, President Reagan visited Canada on his first official trip abroad. He came to complain to Pierre Elliott Trudeau, then Prime Minister.    The United States was angry with its neighbor over an energy policy intended to discourage foreign ownership and a restrictive attitude toward foreign investment in general and also over aggressive takeover moves by Canadian companies - abetted by the Government and big banks - against American concerns.    Four days before that meeting, Washington underscored its displeasure by scrapping an East Coast fisheries treaty between the two nations.

lead_paragraph: In today's world, there is no way that we can
abstract: In today's world, there is no way that we can   successfully address international political   problems without giving full weight to the economic issues,'' Richard A. Debs, president of Morgan Stanley International, recently told the Senate Foreign Relations Committee. ''Nor is there any way we can address international economic problems without considering the political issues.''   This may be a truism but, as Mr. Debs said, ''unfortunately it is a truism that is often neglected in the way we run our government.'' However, useful truth lies not in generalities but in the details.

lead_paragraph: THE ECONOMY The President's budget director warned the Fed not to raise interest rates, saying such action could cause a recession. The Reagan aide, James C. Miller 3d, seemed to be positioning the Administration to blame the Fed if a recession occurs in 1988, an election year. Paul A. Volcker has indicated that the Fed might have to consider pushing up rates to combat the dollar's slide. [ Page A1. ] The F.C.C. voted to raise the monthly telephone access fee to $3.50, from $2, for residential and small-business users. The commission said the increase would generally be offset by a further decline of at least 15 percent in rates for long-distance calls. [ D1. ] The F.C.C. adopted tighter curbs on the broadcast of explicit language about sex and body functions. [ A1. ] Housing construction fell 3.2 percent in March, the biggest decline in six months and the first since November. [ D1. ] Factories, mines and utilities operated at 79.2 percent of capacity last month, off 0.5 percent. [ D3. ] Business sales climbed a record 4.4 percent in February, while inventories rose a small 0.2 percent. [ D3. ] The U.S. will allow patents for animals, clearing the way for inventors to patent life forms created through gene splicing. [ A1. ] COMPANIES A. H. Robins filed a plan to satisfy creditor claims by allotting $1.75 billion for women who contend they were injured by using its Dalkon Shield birth control device. Lawyers for a class of the Dalkon Shield claimants said they would fight the plan, which was filed in bankruptcy court. [ D1. ] A swindle scheme involving fraudulent promissory notes for Indonesia with a face value of $3.5 billion was disclosed by investigators. The authorities said the scheme was run by a Middle Eastern businessman who has previously been linked to the P.L.O. [ D1. ] G.M. will scrap its executive bonus system in favor of a stock option plan, The bonus plan, in effect since 1918, has long been criticized by consumer activists and labor leaders. [ D1. ] Bic said it had 42 lawsuits outstanding that were brought on behalf of people burned or killed by fires allegedly caused by malfunctioning disposable butane lighters that it made. [ D3. ] Net income fell 21.4 percent at American Express, but last year's first quarter included a large one-time gain. [ D2. ] Two tobacco conglomerates, Philip Morris and RJR Nabisco, showed strong gains for the quarter. [ D2. ] Texas Instruments posted an $83.8 million profit, compared with a year-earlier loss, helped by the settlement of patent infringement lawsuits. [ D2. ] Pacific Telesis reported a 7.1 percent earnings gain, while Southwestern Bell reported a 3.4 percent decline. [ D2. ] Borg-Warner agreed to provide GAF with confidential data about itself for GAF to consider a new takeover bid. [ D3. ] Time Inc.'s editor in chief, Henry A. Grunwald, will retire in December. Jason McManus was named as his successor. [ B5. ] Agents arrested 16 stockbrokers on charges of selling cocaine and trading it for stocks and information. [ A1. ] MARKETS The jittery stock, bond and currency markets calmed following a comment by Treasury Secretary Baker that ''a further decline of the dollar'' could be ''counterproductive.'' The dollar strengthened against the yen and the West German mark. Gold rose modestly in New York after falling $4 to $6 an ounce in Europe. [ D1. ] Stocks ended mixed in pre-holiday trading. Several positive events including a stronger dollar and lower interest rates, failed to support blue-chip equities. The Dow Jones industrial average dropped 6.96 points, to 2,275.99. [ D4. ] Treasury issues continued to recover, with intermediate maturities showing some of the best gains of the day. [ D10. ] Grain and soybean futures prices rallied, lifted by expectations of wheat sales to the Soviet Union. [ D11. ] TODAY'S COLUMNS The computer chip dispute may be just the start of U.S. action against Japan in the high-technology area. Washington's impending tariffs, expected today, may make the trade question an important one for GATT. Leonard Silk. Economic Scene. [ D2. ] Mutual funds were highly favored for I.R.A. investments because of the market's surge this year. In past years, when interest rates were much higher, fixed-income funds and money market funds were more dominant. Market Place. [ D4. ]

lead_paragraph: Starting this month, 135 business students at the University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School-- about one-sixth of the entering M.B.A. class -- will become guinea pigs for a new way of teaching global business skills. They will forgo all international courses. Instead, their marketing professor will discuss the pros and cons of having one brand name worldwide. Their operations course will explore foreign distribution systems. In finance, they'll learn to plan for currency fluctuations. The program will culminate in a four-week trip abroad.
abstract: Starting this month, 135 business students at the University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School-- about one-sixth of the entering M.B.A. class -- will become guinea pigs for a new way of teaching global business skills. They will forgo all international courses. Instead, their marketing professor will discuss the pros and cons of having one brand name worldwide. Their operations course will explore foreign distribution systems. In finance, they'll learn to plan for currency fluctuations. The program will culminate in a four-week trip abroad.   "There are no purely domestic or purely international decisions anymore," said David J. Reibstein, a Wharton vice dean, who expects the experimental curriculum to become de rigueur in a few years. "Even a brand manager who never leaves Cincinnati deals with global issues these days."

lead_paragraph: In an unusually blunt discussion, economists and central bank officials from various countries expressed concern over the weekend that the regional trading blocs emerging in Europe, North America and Asia could eventually destroy the world's free-trade system.
abstract: In an unusually blunt discussion, economists and central bank officials from various countries expressed concern over the weekend that the regional trading blocs emerging in Europe, North America and Asia could eventually destroy the world's free-trade system.   A few of those attending the Federal Reserve's annual summer conference, including the keynote speaker, went a step further. They argued that the 40-year-old free-trade system, in which more than 90 nations jointly agree to lower tariffs simultaneously, had outlived its usefulness and should give way to these regional trading blocs. The blocs can use tariffs to keep out imports from nations that are not members. Europe, North America Cited     These economists said that the European Community and the emerging United States-Mexico-Canada trading zone were already proving more effective than the older free-trade system, known as the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, on two important counts. The blocs are generating huge increases in trade among neighboring countries, which are natural trading partners anyway. And, the economists said, regional blocs are becoming a way to exclude Japanese competitors, whose products receive equal treatment in the free-trade system.

lead_paragraph: When senior officials from industrialized nations meet this week to discuss aid to the Soviet Union, they are likely to disagree on whether to provide large-scale financial assistance but strongly endorse technical assistance and humanitarian aid.
abstract: When senior officials from industrialized nations meet this week to discuss aid to the Soviet Union, they are likely to disagree on whether to provide large-scale financial assistance but strongly endorse technical assistance and humanitarian aid.   Advice and training for Soviet officials seeking to rescue their country's foundering economy is vital to help officials there understand the country's troubles, said a senior Administration official who spoke on condition of anonymity. Technical assistance also provides a way to identify the problems and possible solutions while waiting for either the central Government or the republics to emerge as responsible recipients for aid, he added.

abstract: If it wanted to, America could exert more leverage over Chinese human rights practices than any other country in the world. The hard currency Beijing earns through its $18 billion trade surplus with the U.S. is a key ingredient in China's development strategy. By carefully linking China's privileges to achievable human rights objectives, Washington could encourage reform-minded forces in the world's biggest dictatorship.

lead_paragraph: After intense pressure from the White House, some leading Congressional critics of the North American Free Trade Agreement are toning down their oratory. A few of them are even saying they might support the pact after all.
abstract: After intense pressure from the White House, some leading Congressional critics of the North American Free Trade Agreement are toning down their oratory. A few of them are even saying they might support the pact after all.   Representative Richard A. Gephardt, the House majority leader, said in an interview late today that he was urging Democrats to avoid taking positions now on the pact, which would eliminate trade barriers among Canada, Mexico and the United States. lead_paragraph: Since taking office, the Clinton Administration's message to American business has been unambiguous: "Follow the Sun." At every opportunity the Clinton team has described the Asia-Pacific region as the nation's most lucrative economic frontier. But a new study published today challenges that thesis, by amassing trade data that suggest that Europe remains America's most important economic partner and will be for years to come.
abstract: Since taking office, the Clinton Administration's message to American business has been unambiguous: "Follow the Sun." At every opportunity the Clinton team has described the Asia-Pacific region as the nation's most lucrative economic frontier. But a new study published today challenges that thesis, by amassing trade data that suggest that Europe remains America's most important economic partner and will be for years to come.   The Economic Strategy Institute, a private research group financed by American corporations, compared Asia and Western Europe in categories like trade, foreign direct investment in the United States, American direct investment abroad and technology transfers. The study concluded that the links between the United States and Europe benefited the American economy far more than those between the United States and Asia.

lead_paragraph: The Supreme Court ruled today that the Federal Communications Commission acted without legal authority when it moved to enhance competition in the long-distance telephone market by relieving AT&T's competitors of the need to file tariffs listing their rates and services.
abstract: The Supreme Court ruled today that the Federal Communications Commission acted without legal authority when it moved to enhance competition in the long-distance telephone market by relieving AT&T's competitors of the need to file tariffs listing their rates and services.   The 5-to-3 decision was a victory for AT&T, which had fought the deregulatory initiative through several rounds of court battles. The ruling leaves the matter to Congress, where the issue could complicate the debate over big telecommunications measures that are pending in both Houses. Setback to MCI Unit    In addition to the F.C.C., a loser in the Court today was the MCI Telecommunications Corporation, a unit of the MCI Communications Corporation, which had used its new rate-setting leeway to compete with AT&T by negotiating customized service agreements with big companies.

lead_paragraph: COMPANIES At Simon & Schuster, a Pawn in the Corporate Game Publishing sometimes seems a world apart, exempt from big-money corporate chess games. But the outside world crashed in on this literary island last week when Viacom, which recently acquired Simon & Schuster as part of its Paramount package, swooped into the publishing house and sacked the man who'd built it into a powerhouse in recent decades, Richard E. Snyder. The publishing world's reaction: shock, mystification -- and jitters about the fate of various authors. Viacom gave a well-worn explanation: a difference in styles. But it soon spied a gathering storm, and moved quickly to calm it, going out of its way to state its "commitment to literature and the printed word." Of course, not everyone at Simon & Schuster mourned, as some were glad to bid farewell to what they called Mr. Snyder's explosive temper. They expected his successor, Jonathan Newcomb, to set a softer tone.

lead_paragraph: The class content of a Pat Buchanan rally is so thick you can smell it. It smells like motor oil. Or so it does this February afternoon on the floor of a transmission factory in Fort Dodge, Iowa, where the air tools hiss, the employees wear coveralls and Buchanan confers upon them the proud title "worker." He issues his usual condemnations of corporate greed and pokes fun at Steve Forbes, his impossibly rich rival, for cooking up his ideas with "the boys down at the yacht club." He even solicits Democratic votes by mocking his own party's plutocratic past. "You can join the party of greed for one evening!"
abstract: The class content of a Pat Buchanan rally is so thick you can smell it. It smells like motor oil. Or so it does this February afternoon on the floor of a transmission factory in Fort Dodge, Iowa, where the air tools hiss, the employees wear coveralls and Buchanan confers upon them the proud title "worker." He issues his usual condemnations of corporate greed and pokes fun at  Steve Forbes, his impossibly rich rival, for cooking up his ideas with "the boys down at the yacht club." He even solicits Democratic votes by mocking his own party's plutocratic past. "You can join the party of greed for one evening!"         But when I approach Buchanan and note, perhaps with a trace of grudging admiration, that he has brought a new class sensibility to the election, he blanches. Actually, he puckers. "Class sensibility?" he says, spitting out the phrase like a bad olive. Though Buchanan is rarely at a loss for words, this stops him cold. "I don't think I want to go anywhere near that one." Instead, he climbs back into his bus and resumes his underdog campaign, on behalf of those who "work with their hands and tools and machines."

snippet: GLOBAL TRADE STEEL TARIFF CASE ADVANCES The World Trade Organization has agreed to the European Union's request to set up a panel of experts in the trans-Atlantic dispute over United States steel tariffs. The Bush administration had blocked the un...
lead_paragraph: GLOBAL TRADE
abstract: GLOBAL TRADE STEEL TARIFF CASE ADVANCES The World Trade Organization has agreed to the European Union's request to set up a panel of experts in the trans-Atlantic dispute over United States steel tariffs. The Bush administration had blocked the union's initial request, as it is allowed to do under trade rules, but the second request automatically leads to the establishment of a panel. The United States also denied requests by Japan and South Korea for a similar panel. Unless an agreement is reached, those requests will be automatically granted later this month.   Elizabeth Olson (NYT) ASIAJAPAN: NASDAQ AT ODDS WITH EXCHANGE Nasdaq Japan threatened to leave the Osaka Securities Exchange for another Japanese stock market if the Osaka exchange continues to delay changes in trading rules that Nasdaq wants. Nasdaq Japan, owned by the Nasdaq market of the United States, the Japanese Internet company Softbank and 13 securities companies, began trading two years ago as a section of the Osaka Securities Exchange. Nasdaq Japan wants the Osaka exchange to adopt a trading system that would allow dealers to act more freely in transactions, but the exchange has been reluctant, a Nasdaq Japan spokeswoman, Naho Yohda, said. The changes are central to Nasdaq's plant to create a global exchange. An Osaka exchange spokesman, Tsutomu Konishi, said the exchange had received no word from Nasdaq.   (AP) CHINA: G.M. BUYS STAKE IN AUTOMAKER General Motors said it would buy a $30 million stake in a Chinese minivan and minitruck maker, moving into the largest sector of China's auto market. General Motors said it would take a 34 percent stake in SAIC-Wuling Automotive, based in the southern province of Guangxi. The original Chinese owners, the Shanghai Automotive Industry Corporation and Wuling Automotive, will retain a controlling 66 percent share. snippet: World Trade Organization automatically agrees to European Union's second request to set up panel of experts in dispute over United States steel tariffs; US blocked first request (S)
lead_paragraph: The World Trade Organization has agreed to the European Union's request to set up a panel of experts in the trans-Atlantic dispute over United States steel tariffs. The Bush administration had blocked the union's initial request, as it is allowed to do under trade rules, but the second request automatically leads to the establishment of a panel. The United States also denied requests by Japan and South Korea for a similar panel. Unless an agreement is reached, those requests will be automatically granted later this month. Elizabeth Olson (NYT)

snippet: Prime Minister Stephen Harper said he would introduce legislation to carry out an agreement to end a dispute over softwood lumber exports to the United States. The agreement, which replaces American import duties with a Canadian export tax, is con...
lead_paragraph: Prime Minister Stephen Harper said he would introduce legislation to carry out an agreement to end a dispute over softwood lumber exports to the United States. The agreement, which replaces American import duties with a Canadian export tax, is controversial in Canada. Among other reasons, many Canadians were dismayed that the American government would keep about $1 billion of the $5 billion in duties it has collected. Several international trade rulings have said that the American tariff violates trade rules. Mr. Harper, left, originally required the support of 95 percent of Canada’s softwood lumber exporters before introducing legislation, but recently his government dropped that requirement. On Tuesday, Mr. Harper, who did not answer questions, said he had “a clear majority of support from companies in all regions.” Opposition parties in Canada’s minority Parliament oppose the agreement. Mr. Harper said that his government would resign if the softwood bill was not passed. That would force an immediate election, an event the currently leaderless Liberal Party, which leads the opposition, would rather avoid.

lead_paragraph: Prime Minister Stephen Harper said he would introduce legislation to carry out an agreement to end a dispute over softwood lumber exports to the United States. The agreement, which replaces American import duties with a Canadian export tax, is controversial in Canada. Among other reasons, many Canadians were dismayed that the American government would keep about $1 billion of the $5 billion in duties it has collected. Several international trade rulings have said that the American tariff violates trade rules. Mr. Harper, left, originally required the support of 95 percent of Canada's softwood lumber exporters before introducing legislation, but recently his government dropped that requirement. On Tuesday, Mr. Harper, who did not answer questions, said he had "a clear majority of support from companies in all regions." Opposition parties in Canada's minority Parliament oppose the agreement. Mr. Harper said that his government would resign if the softwood bill was not passed. That would force an immediate election, an event the currently leaderless Liberal Party, which leads the opposition, would rather avoid.
abstract: Canadian Prime Minister Stephen Harper says he will introduce legistlation to carry out agreement to end dispute over softwood lumber exports to United States; says his government will resign if bill is not passed; photo (M)

lead_paragraph: ASEAN: This week's meeting of economic ministers from Southeast Asia in Kuala Lumpur was not short on ambition. The officials confirmed a desire to accelerate the creation of a European-style single market to 2015 as the region struggles to strengthen its economic muscle. The plan will involve removing non-tariff-related barriers and quickening the opening up of service industries. The next logical step would be a single-currency system. Tokyo also entered into the spirit by proposing the creation of a 16-country free trade area comprising Japan, China, India, South Korea, New Zealand, Australia and the Association of South East Asian Nations. But the Southeast Asians must try to learn the hard lessons of Europe's experience. There, the long road to a single market started in the early 1950s with the European Coal and Steel Community; and it is still struggling to bring down barriers. In 2000, the EU introduced the Lisbon Agenda, which sought to turn the bloc into the world's premier knowledge-based economy by 2010. But there has been no shortage of setbacks to the goal, from lacking agreement on a communitywide patent system to a weakened agreement on services to a lack of common takeover rules. Corporate nationalism appears to be back on the scene. The Asean region faces far more obstacles than Europe ever did. It comprises 10 countries - one of which is an international pariah - in highly different stages of development, with deep cultural and linguistic differences and no shortage of internal bickering. The trade ministers' meeting was overshadowed this week by a dispute between Malaysia and Thailand over automobile tariffs, and Malaysia and Singapore have a history of simmering mistrust. Malaysia has also said that it will not give up its affirmative action policy to help contractors who are Malays or belong to other indigenous groups. The success of the project will also involve Japan, China and South Korea acting in concert to support and nurture the body - something they have not proved adept at in the past. Ambition is no bad thing, but an excess of ambition can only disappoint. Ask the EU.

snippet: Volvo Cars will merge its engine development and manufacturing assets with those of parent Geely, creating a division to supply in-house brands Lotus, LEVC, Lynk and Proton, and also potential rivals with next-generation combustion and hybrid engi...
lead_paragraph: FRANKFURT — Volvo Cars will merge its engine development and manufacturing assets with those of parent Geely, creating a division to supply in-house brands Lotus, LEVC, Lynk and Proton, and also potential rivals with next-generation combustion and hybrid engines. It marks the latest example of consolidation in the engine manufacturing sector as tighter emissions rules hike development costs at a time when the expansion of electric cars calls into question the long-term demand for gas guzzlers.
